<AbstractNarration>The feasibility of a novel approach for developing a new generation of cutting tool coatings will be explored.  This approach is based on an innovative composite coating of superhard cubic boron nitride (cBN) nano-sized particulates with titanium nitride (TiN) phase matrix along with a science-based new methodology for cutting tool design, specific for hard machining.  The investigators propose to explore if the new electrostatic-based coating method will work by resolving the agglomeration problem for submicron particle sizes, and to determine if such coated tools can compete commercially.  This is a collaborative research program to be performed by Purdue University and University of Arkansas.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;If successful, this approach may provide an economical way to synthesize protective coatings on cutting tools, far less expensive than traditional chemical or physical vapor deposition.  Such high-performance cutting tools reduce frequency of tool replacement and improve productivity.&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
